The following anatomical landmarks are useful for defining maps, as well as defining various category-selective regions. Anatomy can vary a lot among subjects. Example labeled anatomies can be found in Projects/7t/ppt/prf_vm_meshImages.pptx and in the supplementary information for this paper.  Parietal occipital sulcus (POS):  large sulcus that is border between occipital and parietal lobes. Typically easy to identify. Calcarine  sulcus  (calc) : location of V1. Often forms acute angle with POS, which can be helpful for identifying it.  Lingual gyrus  (ling) : large and twisty gyrus ventral to calcarine. V2v and V3v are here. Runs roughly parallel to the calcarine. Collateral sulcus (CoS):  giant and probably most easily identifiable sulcus running along ventral surface of temporal lobe. Ventral maps VO1/2 and PHC1/2 run roughly perpendicular to CoS. The Parahippocampal Place Area (PPA), despite its name, is usually on CoS. Parahippocampal gyrus (PHG):  gyrus medial to CoS. Next to hippocampus. The PPA was original found here, but is generally localized more lateral in CoS. Fusiform gyrus (Fus):  gyrus lateral to CoS, typically broken up by one of more "island" sulci. Face-selective areas FFA-1 and FFA-2 are located in the fusiform, located posterior and anterior of the mid-fusiform sulcus (mfus) respectively ( ref ). Limb/body-selective areas are found between these face-selective regions ( ref ). Inferior temporal sulcus  (ITS):  sulcus lateral to fusiform. The Visual Word Form Area (VWFA) is found in the posterior bit of this sulcus ( ref ). Inferior occipital gyrus (IOG):  roughy perpendicular to lingual and parallel to ptCos. V4 is typically here, as well as a face-selective patch. Sometimes also a word-selective patch. Posterior transverse collateral sulcus (ptCos):  "hook" like sulcus extending ventrally off the posterior bit of CoS. Marks border between hV4 and VO1, as discussed further below and in this paper. Ventral maps V1, V2v, and V3v V1, V2v, and V3v are probably the easiest maps to define. Borders occur at at polar angle reversals. Note how polar angle stripes (right) run roughly perpendicular to eccentricity stripes (middle). This is a general principle of retinotopy.  V1:  A hemifield located in the calcarine sulcus. Note how there are approximate three "stripes" in the polar angle map, indicating lower, middle, and upper parts of the visual field V2v:  A quarterfield ventral to V1. Covers the upper contralateral quarterfield. Note how border between V2v and V1 is about midway through the polar angle reversal, here shown in cyan–>green–>cyan (upper-->middle–>upper visual field) from superior to inferior. V3v:  A quarterfield ventral to V2v. Covers to the upper contralateral quaterfield, like V2v.  hV4 See also: More on hV4 This is where it gets tricky. Defining hV4 is tricky for a couple reasons: (1) the polar angle bands don't run parallel with V1-V3, (2) hV4 doesn't extend as far posterior as V1-V3, and (3) hV4 is defined using the eccentricity reversal rather than the polar angle reversal. On top of these problems, some people  think hV4 is a quarterfield like V2v and V3v and analogous to monkey V4 ( Brewer et al, 2005 , Hansen et al, 2007) . hV4 also runs along IOG, which in many people is under the transverse sinus (TS) ( Winawer et al, 2010 ). This large, draining sinus can cause significant distortion in the magnetic field, leading to low mean signal and low coherence. It is therefore sometimes difficult to measure a lower visual field representation in hV4, which incidentally plays right hV4 being a quarterfield.  The model to keep in mind is shown in the figure above, stolen from Witthoft et al (2013) . The polar angle bands (b), form concentric, inverted U's. The anterior border of hV4 runs through the apex of these U's. It also runs through the reversal of eccentricity bands (a): V1, V2, V3, and hV4 share a foveal representation, called the "confluent fovea." VO1 and VO2 share a different foveal representation, the VO fovea. The border between hV4 and VO1 is where these two foveal representations get smushed together. Finally, this eccentricity reversal generally falls in ptCos, so identifying this landmark can be particularly useful for defining hV4.   In the figure above, ptCos is marked in red (left). The same sulcus is marked in the eccentricity map (middle), overlapping the eccentricity reversal (blue, indicating peripheral) between the confluent fovea (red towards occipital pole) and VO fovea (red, more anterior). The border between hV4 and VO1 lies along this reversal. In the polar angle map (right), note how the polar angle bands bend in inverted U's across the hV4 border. In many subjects, hV4 is somewhat more difficult to define. Witthoft et al (2013) has a number of images with more difficult-to-define hV4's.  VO1 and VO2 Once you've got hV4 down, VO1 and VO2 are relatively straightforward. The border between VO1 and VO2 can be readily identified in the polar angle map: running along the ventral border of V3v, there's a "T" or inverted "L" band representing the upper visual field (green, highlighted with red lines in the image below to the right). The long leg of this T/L is the border between VO1 and VO2. VO1 and VO2 share a foveal representation, the VO fovea. VO1 and VO2 should run roughly perpendicular to CoS.  VO1: hemifield anterior hV4 and abutting ventral border of V3v. The border between VO1 and VO2 is the polar angle reversal, which often appears as a "T" or inverted "L," as indicated in red above right image. VO2 :   hemifield anterior to VO1.  PHC-1 and PHC-2 Two hemifield even more anterior to VO2, sharing a third foveal representation, the PHC fovea. PHC1 and 2 are roughly parallel to VO1 and 2, running perpendicular across CoS.
